                                Palette

        Sets the Workbench colours. The number of available colours is
determined by the screen mode in use.

Workbench 2.x:-
                Point to a colour in the selection gadget, and click the
selection button. The selected colour will be shown in the display box to
the left of the  selection gadget. By changing the values of the slider you
can change the amount of red, blue and green used in the selected colour.
As you drag the bar through the slider box, the colour on the display box
and on the screen will change.

Workbench 3.x:-

                This is much different to 2.x. The top left of the Palette
editor window is the four and eight current Workbench colours. The top
right has a Colour Mode cycle gadget with two setting: Multicolour Setting
and 4 Colour Settings. The Multicolour Setting gadget is for setting eight
Workbench colours. The 4 Colour Setting gadget is for setting four
Workbench colours.

Using the RGB and HSBmode to change colour:-

                Point to a colour in the selection gadget and click the
selection button, then use the slider gadget to change the selected colour.
The colour in the display box and on the sample screen changes as the bar
is dragged through the slider box.

Using the Colour wheel:-

                Point to a colour in the selection gadget and click the
selection button then point to the colour intensity indicator within the
colour wheel and hold down the selection button, moving the mouse pointer
moves the indicator on the colour wheel, changing the colour in the display
box and on the sample screen as the indicator moves. Release the selection
button when you reach the colour you want.


